text: to update a propertyAddress, you can use this command for postgre sql .  UPDATE housingData AS a SET propertyAddress = COALESCE(a.propertyAddress, b.propertyAddress) FROM housingData AS b WHERE a.parcelID = b.parcelID    AND a.uniqueID <> b.uniqueID    AND a.propertyAddress IS NULL;

author: @user-zz5lp6rt3o
text: For those using MySQL and stuck on deleting duplicates using a CTE, this worked for me:   WITH rownumcte AS ( SELECT UniqueID , 	ROW_NUMBER() OVER ( 	PARTITION BY ParcelID,  	PropertyAddress,  	SalePrice,         SaleDate,         LegalReference       ORDER BY UniqueID) as rownum FROM nashville_housing_data) DELETE hd FROM nashville_housing_data hd INNER JOIN rownumcte r ON hd.UniqueID = r.UniqueID where rownum>1;  Hope it helps!

author: @user-rl2kq1mg9s
text: Hi Alex. First and foremost, thank you for developing these videos! They've been incredibly helpful as I'm learning the building blocks to become a junior data analyst. I am working through a dataset for the Google certification case study and have a similar null value issue with my data cleaning, similar to what is covered around 18:29 of this video.   I used your code as a guideline, but am coming up with an error because an alias I created from concatenating two columns in my first query is not recognized in the second query. Do you have any tips on how to fix this issue so my second query will run correctly? Below is my code:  ```` SELECT ride_id, start_station_name, end_station_name, CONCAT(start_lat, ', ', start_lng) as start_GPS, CONCAT(end_lat, ', ', end_lng) as end_GPS FROM    `rideshare-data-398317.2022_Rideshare_data.2022_01` ORDER BY   ride_id   -- Almost found a way to find the missing station name null values, need a way to recognize "start_GPS" alias from the previous query  SELECT a.start_station_name, CONCAT(start_lat,' ', start_lng) as a.start_GPS,  b.start_station_name,  CONCAT(start_lat,' ', start_lng) as b.start_GPS,  ISNULL(a.start_station_name, b.start_station_name) FROM    `rideshare-data-398317.2022_Rideshare_data.2022_01` AS a Join   `rideshare-data-398317.2022_Rideshare_data.2022_01` AS b  ON   a.start_GPS = b.start_GPS   AND a.ride_id <> b.ride_id WHERE a.start_station_name IS NULL ````

text: 9:05 Not sure if this has been pointed out, but the reason the SaleDate column didn't "update" here is because UPDATE does not change data types. author: @shanemanske5262
text: Postgres way of deleting duplicates:   DELETE FROM nash WHERE uniqueid IN     (SELECT uniqueid     FROM         (SELECT uniqueid,          ROW_NUMBER() OVER( PARTITION BY parcelid, propertyaddress, saleprice, saledate, legalreference         ORDER BY  uniqueid ) AS row_number         FROM nash ) t         WHERE t.row_number > 1 );

text: For anyone doing this project in Postgres‚Ä¶.   the ISNULL function does not seem to work.  After some extensive trial and error, I got this to wor k.  It‚Äôs basically an implicit self join with the update:  UPDATE nashville_housing2 AS t1  SET "PropertyAddress" = t2."PropertyAddress" FROM nashville_housing2 AS t2 where  t1."UniqueID " != t2."UniqueID " AND t1."PropertyAddress" is null  Cheers!

text: For those who would like to showcase regular expressions in their projects,  here's a use case:  --for extracting address ALTER TABLE housing_data ADD property_split_address VARCHAR(128); UPDATE housing_data SET property_split_address = SUBSTRING(property_address FROM '(.+),');  --for extracting city   ALTER TABLE housing_data ADD property_split_city VARCHAR(128); UPDATE housing_data SET property_split_city = SUBSTRING(property_address FROM ',\s(.+\S$)');
